{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17595573","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17595573"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:05:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:05:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15366"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15366","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15366"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.06,0.31,0.26,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8057"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67140"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8057","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8057"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15366"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52596"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"6978"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19563"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19565"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22467"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67140","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67140"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe spleen is normally impalpable on physical examination. There are a number of diseases that can cause massive splenomegaly (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Portal hypertension is the commonest cause of splenomegaly in Australia","The spleen enlarges towards the right upper quadrant","The spleen must enlarge to three times its normal size to become palpable below the costal margin","The spleen enlarges directly anteriorly towards the umbilicus","The normal sized spleen can be palpated in the left 9th intercostal space"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe spleen normally lies between the 9th and 11th ribs in the left upper quadrant of the abdomen. It is not normally evident by physical examination. However, any dullness to percussion in this region on full inspiration would indicate possible splenic enlargement.  When the spleen enlarges, it does so in a predictable manner, extending inferiorly and medially towards the right iliac fossa.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe spleen\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Emust enlarge to three times\u003C/strong\u003E the normal size before it becomes palpable below the left costal margin. The spleen does not enlarge \u003Cstrong\u003Etowards the right upper quadrant\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Edirectly anteriorly\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst portal hypertension is an important cause of splenomegaly, most cases are usually due to infection (eg infectious mononucleosis) or malignancy (eg lymphoma).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The spleen must enlarge 2-3 times its normal size before becoming palpable below the left costal margin","The normal spleen lies between ribs 9-11 in the left upper quadrant","Splenomegaly follows a predictable path of enlargement from the left upper quadrant towards the right iliac fossa"],"references":["Chapman J, Goyal A, Azevedo AM. Splenomegaly. 2023 Jun 26. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28613657.","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52596"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15366"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21283"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21283","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21283"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/FbPokREN1WP5fNHNJRrii63FXeDf9k.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/FbPokREN1WP5fNHNJRrii63FXeDf9k.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":467}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52596","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52596"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-03T18:02:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-03T18:03:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8057"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67140"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":